			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">some Video processing chip etc are not common practice anymore (or hard to find)?</div><br /><br />Yup pretty much. All graphics chips from the 80s with NES-like capabilities are no longer in production. It is possible though to find certain chips like the 6845 and 6847 for sale at some online stores, though they aren't really good for games. The 6847 is characters only with no sprites, and has only 9 colors. The 6845 is character based as well, but requires extra video hardware to display the actual pixels. All it does is send character indexes to the external signal-producing hardware and generate horizontal and vertical sync pulses. It is flexible but not very powerful. The TMS9918A, along with the V9938 and V9958 are better but harder to find. The TMS9918A was used in the MSX, TI 99/4A, and Colecovision, so games for those consoles should give you an idea of its power. It has tile graphics and sprites, but it has only two colors per tile (one if you use transparency) and a palette of 15 colors. The V99x8 series is awesome and is slightly more powerful than the NES's PPU, but isn't that common, as far as I know. From what I've read the series was only used in upgraded versions of the MSX and TI 99/4A.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">What would be really cool is a NES style system with 4BPP graphics even if there were no attributes (so you could have one 16 color palette for the entire background). Then perhaps the same would go for sprites.</div>
<br />
<br />That's actually pretty close to what the V9958 is like. It has only 32 8x8 sprites, though.</div>

